{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626692"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:40:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:40:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17090"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17090","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17090"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.02,0,0.98,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9780"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77353"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9780"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17090"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62860"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5059"},{"type":"tags","id":"5124"},{"type":"tags","id":"5132"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22958"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23179"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77353","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77353"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDopamine antagonists are commonly prescribed medications in both hospital and community settings.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the therapeutic mechanism of dopamine antagonists when used as antiemetic agents?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increases dopamine release in the area postrema","Blocks histamine receptors in the vestibular system","Stimulates serotonin receptors in the gut","Blocks dopamine D2 receptors in chemoreceptor trigger zone","Reduces gastric acid secretion"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDopamine antagonists like metoclopramide and domperidone work primarily by \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking dopamine D2 receptors in the chemoreceptor trigger zone\u003C/strong\u003E of the area postrema. This reduces nausea and vomiting signals to the vomiting centre in the medulla.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases dopamine release in the area postrema\u003C/strong\u003E would actually worsen nausea and vomiting rather than provide therapeutic benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks histamine receptors in the vestibular system\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of antihistamines used for motion sickness, not dopamine antagonists.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates serotonin receptors in the gut\u003C/strong\u003E represents the mechanism of 5-HT4 receptor agonists like prucalopride.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduces gastric acid secretion\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of acid-suppressing medications like proton pump inhibitors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile some dopamine antagonists may have effects on gastrointestinal motility via peripheral dopamine receptors, their antiemetic properties are primarily due to central D2 receptor blockade in the chemoreceptor trigger zone.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dopamine antagonists block D2 receptors in the chemoreceptor trigger zone to reduce nausea and vomiting.","Dopamine antagonists like metoclopramide and domperidone increase gastrointestinal motility by acting on peripheral dopaminergic receptors.","The antiemetic effects of dopamine antagonists are primarily mediated through central D2 receptor blockade."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62860"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17090"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62860","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62860"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T17:31:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T17:32:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9780"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77353"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"descript